'''Ras Abu Jarjur''' is a [[reverse osmosis plant|reverse osmosis]] water [[desalination]] plant in [[Bahrain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/NewsDetails.aspx?storyid=223994|title=$2bn power bid|date=25 July 2008|accessdate=22 August 2012|work=[[Gulf Daily News]]|first=Soman|last=Baby}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.desalination.biz/news/magazine_article.asp?id=4702|title=Experience helps boost production and stability at Ras Abu Jarjur|date=18 January 2009|accessdate=22 August 2012|work=Desalination & Water Reuse|first1=Abdulmajeed Ali|last1=Alawadhi|first2=Eng Ali Redha|last2=Hussain}}</ref> The plant produces 16.3 million [[imperial gallon]]s of [[desalination|desalinated]] [[drinking water]] per day.{{fact|date=January 2015}} At the time of its commissioning in the mid-1980s it was the largest reverse osmosis plant in the Middle East with a production capacity of 10 million imperial gallons per day.{{fact|date=January 2015}}

